Sure! You can use the `chessboard` package in LaTeX to create a chessboard and the `chessfss` package to read FEN notation. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do it:

1. First, you need to include the necessary packages in the preamble of your LaTeX document.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessfss}
\usepackage{chessboard}
```

2. Write the `document` section, where you'll draw the board using the `chessboard` command. You'll also read the FEN notation using the `fenboard` command.

```latex
\begin{document}
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}
\showboard
\end{document}
```

Here, the `fenboard` command is used to set up the board according to the FEN string `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR`. This FEN represents the standard starting position of a chess game. 

After that, the `showboard` command is used to actually draw the board. 

Here's the full LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessfss}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}
\showboard
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a chessboard in the standard starting position. You can replace the FEN string with any other valid FEN string to generate the board in a different state.

